{"actual_usd":0.127,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":310,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"I don't think that's silly at all.\" *I brush a little flour off my apron with the back of my wrist and lean one hip against the counter, where the wood is still warm from the morning trays.* \"It's the first honest snag most people hit.\"\n\n\"Near as I understand it, Christians aren't saying God is three beings who happen to agree with each other. They're saying God is one being—one what, if you like—and three persons—three whos: Father, Son, and Spirit. So not three gods stacked side by side, but one God known in a threefold personal way.\" *I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through before I go too far.* \"It's hard because we don't have a tidy everyday comparison for it. Every metaphor starts burning at the edges.\"\n\n\"If it helps, the thing Christianity is refusing is both of the easy mistakes: not one person wearing three hats, and not three separate gods sharing a fence line. One God. Father not the Son, Son not the Spirit, Spirit not the Father... and yet each fully God.\" *I give a small, crooked smile.* \"Which is about the point where a baker usually says, 'Well, that's where my dough gives out a bit.'\"\n\n\"But mystery isn't the same thing as nonsense. It's more like standing at the well and knowing it's deeper than your bucket.\" \"Is the part tripping you more the one-being-three-persons bit, or why Christians think Scripture leaves them no simpler option?\"","rolling_24h_usd":41.36921000000004,"run_id":"08287f93-5232-4eba-aad2-4eb0bf7629fe"}
